<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1421,538,696]" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">
<emphasis inLineHeading="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="616" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,538,562]" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">Identification.</emphasis>
Our specimens were identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="5" pageNumber="616" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nifefori">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">A. nifefori</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
based on: small dorsal scales, in 21–34 rows; small head plates, with interparietal scale much shorter than width of head between orbits; and subdigital lamellae 16–20 (
<bibRefCitation author="Lazell JD" box="[893,1024,672,696]" pageId="5" pageNumber="616" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref5629" refString="Lazell JD (1969) The genus Phenacosaurus (Sauria, Iguanidae). Breviora 325: 1 - 24" type="journal article" year="1969">Lazell 1969</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
