<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="616" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[812,1420,713,905]" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,923,714,738]" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species occurred in the small forest fragment and in the grassland. Individuals were observed at night, for the first time, resting on leaves and small branches. Specimens varied in color, being various shades of green, yellow, and blue (
<figureCitation box="[1173,1236,847,872]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="5.[168,231,2072,2092]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,1500,2047]" captionTargetId="figure-367@5.[168,1419,1500,2047]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 7. Color variation of Anolis nicefori. Scale bar (on right) = 20 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5394099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5394099/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="616">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). This variability in color has not been previously reported for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
